Their large surface area to volume ratio is a really important factor in
determining how nanoparticles behave — it means that nanoparticles have
different properties to the material in bulk. This is because a much greater
proportion of their atoms are available to interact with substances they come
into contact with. For example, fullerenes have different properties to big
lumps of carbon, and the melting point of gold nanoparticles is much lower
than the bulk material.
